Quellious Server</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(10/17/02 12:40:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=567.topic&index=257>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: missed my point..</span><hr size=1> Zeik states:  &quot;That does mean increased availability, along as the odds being the EXACT same as pulling an ace from a single deck. The second one's odds are alot worse, but they are POSSIBLE instead of 0.&quot;<br>
<br>
And this is why increased availability does not automatically mean increased chances.  Variables come into play.<br>
Your citation that a possibility of 1000 reavers spawning in a week automatically means someone is going to get a jade reaver is flawed because you are failing to take into account variables like people being unable to to stay online continuously for one week, the fact that someone else is likely to pass through etc.<br>
<br>
Kailynn states:  &quot;Your deck of cards analogy doesnt work at all Millikin. It makes no sense in relation to Sev and Reavers. Every time ive been to CoM to help a friend get jade reavers one has dropped within the first 9 kills. Ive killed Sev 4 times and never seen a green scale off him.&quot;<br>
<br>
It does apply.  I've gone on some dozen or so Severilous kills.  He's always dropped at least one scale.  Based on that fact, I could say that he has a 100% drop rate.  I wouldn't say that because its not taking into account times I haven't participated in killing him.<br>
<br>
&quot;1:4 chances off scale on Sev<br>
1:9 chances of jade reaver on Reavers<br>
thats about twice as likely to see a scale drop off Sev as to see a jade reaver off a Reaver.&quot;<br>
<br>
Key word in both cases is chance.  Chance does not mean reality, and law of averages is going to come into play a lot more often in the latter case.<br>
<br>
<br>
Montyy states:  &quot;Yeah Milikin, Syllies 40 rogue twink with her rygorr armor pieces and her uber bloodpoint so much outclasses most player this server.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her gear compared to someone else's of her level has no bearing on the fact that all of your gear is far and away better than the gear available to those classes at the time Kunark came out.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I gues you don't see my point, if a group consisting of the 4 I stated can kill black reavers, than 1 or 2 full groups of people with sub par equipment prolly can.&quot;<br>
<br>
No, I see that point quite clearly.  The part you're glossing over is that while an encounter is trivial to someone with the right gear it is certainly not trivial to someone with lower quality equipment.<br>
<br>
Since you all are so hung up on the concept of &quot;stealing content&quot; (I never said that by the way.) and subjective value of one object versus another look at it this way.  The comparative value doesn't change the act.  If you steal a Rolls Royce or a Nissan Stanza, its still grand theft auto.  And it doesn't matter if you needed help to disable the car alarm or found the keys in the ignition.<br>
<br>
BTW:  Verant doesn't care one iota about manaburn trivializing Kunark dragons for farming.  The nice new triggerable Ragefire complete with old loot tables is proof.<br>
<br>
